1.Very Important Interview Point
A toleration does not force a Pod onto a node.
It only permits the Pod to run there.

Example:
Cluster:
Node1
Node2 (gpu=true)
Pod:
Has gpu toleration
Scheduler may still choose:
Node1
because toleration is only permission, not a placement rule.
How do you force a Pod onto a specific node?
Use Node Affinity or Node Selector together with taints.

Example:
Node
gpu=true
↓
Taint:
gpu=true:NoSchedule
↓
Label:
gpu=true
↓
Pod
NodeAffinity:
gpu=true

Toleration:
gpu=true

Now:

Node Affinity selects the GPU node.
Toleration allows the Pod onto the tainted node.

This combination is common in production.

Remove a taint
kubectl taint nodes worker-2 gpu=true:NoSchedule-

Notice the trailing -.

Check again:

kubectl describe node worker-2

The taint should be gone.

Built-in Taints

Kubernetes automatically applies some taints.

Node Not Ready
node.kubernetes.io/not-ready
Node Unreachable
node.kubernetes.io/unreachable
Memory Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/memory-pressure
Disk Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/disk-pressure
PID Pressure
node.kubernetes.io/pid-pressure

These help prevent new Pods from being scheduled onto unhealthy nodes.

Real Production Examples
1. GPU Nodes
gpu=true:NoSchedule

Only ML/AI workloads with the proper toleration run there.

2. Database Nodes
database=true:NoSchedule

Only database Pods can be scheduled.

3. Monitoring Nodes
monitoring=true:NoSchedule

Only monitoring tools like Prometheus or Grafana agents run there.

4. Spot Instances
spot=true:NoSchedule

Only workloads that can tolerate interruptions are scheduled.


