Interview Questions
Q1. What is a taint?

A taint is applied to a Node to repel Pods unless they have a matching toleration.

Q2. What is a toleration?

A toleration is applied to a Pod to allow it to be scheduled on a tainted node.

Q3. Does a toleration guarantee scheduling on a tainted node?

No. It only allows scheduling. Use Node Affinity or Node Selector to prefer or require a specific node.

Q4. Difference between NoSchedule and NoExecute?
NoSchedule: Blocks new Pods only.
NoExecute: Blocks new Pods and evicts existing Pods that don't tolerate the taint.
Hands-on Lab (Recommended)

To truly understand taints and tolerations, practice this sequence:

Create a namespace:

kubectl create namespace taint-demo
Taint one of your worker nodes with NoSchedule.
Deploy an NGINX Pod without a toleration and observe it stay in Pending.

Describe the Pod:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name> -n taint-demo

Look for an event like:

node(s) had untolerated taint
Add the matching toleration to the Pod manifest and redeploy.
Change the taint effect to NoExecute and observe how existing Pods behave.

Working through these steps will make the scheduling behavior much easier to remember than just reading the theory.
